            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Yasmin Farahpour was born in Berkeley, a child of the Iranian diaspora. Her parents, a physician and an architect, had fled Tehran in 1980, carrying with them the ghost of a life left behind. Her upbringing was a delicate balance: American cartoons and Californian sunshine outside, and a home that was a sanctuary of Persian culture within\u2014fragrant stews, whispered poetry of Hafez, and intricately woven rugs that told stories her parents could not always voice. This domestic museum, filled with beautiful objects tinged with loss, became the foundation of her life's passion.\n\nShe pursued Art History at UCLA before earning a graduate degree in Museum Studies from New York University. Her focus was never in doubt: telling the stories of objects and the cultures that created them. After early-career roles in Washington D.C., she felt the pull of home and accepted a position at San Francisco\u2019s Asian Art Museum. The city, with its own history of reinvention and diverse communities, felt like a natural fit. Over a decade of dedicated work, she rose through the ranks, her recent promotion to Senior Curator marking a personal and professional peak.\n\nNow 41, Yasmin lives in a meticulously curated one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley. Her 2.8-mile commute on the MUNI 21 bus is a daily ritual, a time to observe the city before immersing herself in the quiet, climate-controlled world of West Asian antiquities. Her life is ordered and intentional. Evenings are for gallery openings, lectures, or quiet nights with a small, cherished circle of friends\u2014an academic, a chef, and a software engineer who grounds her scholarly world.\n\nContent in her career, Yasmin\u2019s aspirations are now grander in scope. Her dream is to curate a major exhibition on the art of the Iranian diaspora, a project that would bridge the ancient history she preserves with the modern, scattered identity she embodies. It would be more than a collection of art; it would be a testament to her parents' journey and a map for her own place in the world."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was seven, lying on the living room floor in Berkeley. Her small finger traced a woven bird in the intricate Kirman rug, the wool soft and dense beneath her touch. She asked her mother what the bird meant. Her mother\u2019s voice, explaining it was a bulbul, a symbol of the beloved, was as thin as silk thread. Yasmin felt the weight of a place she\u2019d never seen in that explanation\u2014a beauty so profound it had to be whispered. It was then she learned objects held ghosts.\n\n2.\nAround age 20, in the hushed, cavernous stacks of the UCLA arts library, she stumbled upon a photo of a turquoise-glazed bowl from Nishapur, 10th century. A jolt went through her, sharp and proprietary. It wasn\u2019t a remote artifact; it was a familiar hue, the color of tiles she\u2019d seen in books at home. That night, hunched over the glossy page, she felt an irrational, possessive pride. This wasn't just history; it was her inheritance, and she suddenly knew her life\u2019s work would be to protect it.\n\n3.\nAt 29, after a sterile networking event in D.C., she stood on her balcony in the humid night and called her parents. Hearing the casual Farsi chatter in the background\u2014the sound of tea being poured\u2014she felt a physical ache. It wasn't just homesickness; it was a craving for the particular golden light of the Bay Area, for a culture that felt lived-in, not just visited. She knew then she had to go home. The career she was building felt hollow without the foundation of her own history nearby.\n\n4.\nJust last year, on a foggy morning, the 21-Hayes bus lurched to a stop near Laguna. Through the steamed-up window, Yasmin saw a cross-section of the city: a young tech worker, an elderly Russian woman with her shopping, a mother speaking Tagalog to her child. For a moment, the quiet hum of the bus felt like a gallery of living portraits. The thought struck her with absolute clarity: *we are all diasporas*. This city, her chosen home, was a collection of beautiful, resilient fragments, just like her.\n\n5.\nThe evening she was promoted, she didn't celebrate. Instead, she sat in her silent, perfectly ordered apartment, looking at a small, framed piece of calligraphy her father had given her. The promotion felt less like an achievement and more like a tool she had finally earned. Staring at the elegant, sweeping Farsi script, the idea for her exhibition bloomed, fully formed and urgent. It was time to stop just preserving the ancient past and start assembling the story of its scattered, vibrant present. It was her story to tell."
